T1  - Strategic trade policy: Choosing between export subsidies and export quotas under uncertainty
AU  - Shivakumar, Ram
JO  - Journal of International Economics
VL  - 35
IS  - 1
SP  - 169
EP  - 183
PY  - 1993
DA  - 1993/08/01/
SN  - 0022-1996
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0022-1996(93)90010-U
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/002219969390010U
AB  - I consider a trade policy game in which the choice of policy (subsidy or quota) and time of implementation [before (commit) or after (delay) observing the random demand intercept] is endogenously determined. Each country has four possible options: CQ, CS, DS and DQ, where CQ denotes a commitment to a quota and the other options are similarly labeled. For the special case of an international duopoly, countries prefer quotas to subsidies: CQ is chosen if noise is ‘small’ and DQ if noise is ‘large’. Also interesting is that quotas in the DQ regime coincide with firms' desired exports.
